segments.text: This is January 14, and we're in College Station at 310 Suffolk, and I'm talking with Charles E. Chuck McCandless, whom I think grew up in Dallas.
Chuck, would you give a biographical summary as you recall it until you
got here to be a member of this faculty and staff?
Sure.
I was born in Dallas, Texas, July 26, 1931.
We're in Trinity Heights, which is part of Oak Cliff.
Moved to East Dallas in fifth grade.
Then moved to North Dallas to Alex W. Stevens Junior High School.
Then North Dallas High School.
Graduated from North Dallas.
Then I went my freshman year at Abilene Christian College.
Found that we didn't exactly match up too well.
So I transferred to North Texas State University.
Went there for a year and a half.
And then the Korean police action broke out.
And I volunteered to join the Air Force.
Served in the Air Force for two years, 10 months, and 18 days.
Got out, and by that time had been married.
I had one child when I got out, and my wife was pregnant with our second child.
She was born in February.
In June of 1954, I started at A&M as a physical education major.
Graduated in 56.
Became the junior high school football and basketball coach at Sillsbury, Texas.
After two years I became the counselor and then I left Silsby to go to North Texas State University to pursue my doctorate in counseling.
And in between time I got my master's in counseling from A&M in 1958.
While I was at North Texas I got a phone call from
Carl Landis, and he asked me about an interest in coming back to A&M as director of intramurals.
I told him at the time that I really felt I needed to complete my doctoral work, and so he invited me down for a visit.
I visited with Dr. Landis, Carl Tischler, Frank Hubert,
They made an offer, which I thought was not adequate.
I said no, and thanked them very much for the opportunity.
And got a call back, and they made a better offer.
And I said, I still felt I needed to come back and finish my degree.
And they said, well, what would it take?
And I gave them what I thought was an exorbitant amount
And they said yes, and so they took my crutches away from me, and I came back and found out my exhorter mount was really very, very small.
So that's how I got back to A&E.
You got here when?
In August of 1961.
Describe the campus as it was.
Much smaller than it is now.
I think one of the major things about coming back was something I realized later.
In 1961, we still had no air conditioning with Texas A&M.
But it seemed to me we had about 7,000 students.
At that point, the core was optional, all-male, very large and attractive campus for the size student body we had.
Something not directed right at the university, but there was a clear difference between Bryan and College Station.
Remember the sign that said, strong men say no to strong drink.
So anyway, we'd always thought that College Station would be a great place to rear a family.
And that was probably the driving reason that we came back.
You mentioned Carl Landis.
Tell about him.
what kind of person he was, and what kind of department he was in.
Okay, I'd like to, let me go back and tell one story, which I enjoy at least.
After I got out of the Air Force, I thought, I know I'm going to come back to school, and I had pretty well decided to be Texas, A&M, or North Texas.
I knew about North Texas.
Went to the University of Texas, and the people I met over there were very much like the reputation here by the University of Texas.
not tremendously friendly, and having been an enlisted man in the Air Force, I wanted to be loved and appreciated.
And I came to A&M, and the people I met at A&M were Mr. Penberthy, Spike White, Barney Welch, Pete Hardesty, Carl Landis.
And there was no decision.
A&M was the place for me to be.
I always wondered, though, if I'd gone into the fiscal office
I don't think I would have been an athlete.
So it's interesting how the sequence of events comes out that influence your life forever and ever.
But Carl Landis was one of three professors who I think made a real difference in my life.
As an undergraduate, I was very impressed with his professionalism.
He just exuded professionalism and tried to inculcate that in all of his students.
He really was the one who seemed to me to be most involved with the students in the physical education department.
Only Carl Tishler was the head.
And Carl Landis was a man who was very proud in almost every way.
He was very concerned about his physical appearance.
He was very concerned about his professional appearance.
And the physical facilities were tremendously important.
And I remember him saying, if you ever walked into a gym and saw a sagging volleyball net or a raggedy basketball net, then you knew you didn't have a very good program that you were looking at.
So anyway, his emphasis on professionalism
did a lot to make me feel that I should aspire to the same level.
He was a fairly well-known football official.
Very well known.
Can you talk about that a little?
Yeah, he again took great pride in it.
He was a man who knew his rules and he was very precise and his calls had the same level of
and his officiating, and something that's distantly related.
I remember one summer we were in class in G. Raleigh White, and Carl was somewhat prudish.
And in the classroom behind us was C. K. Est, another football official who was not prudish.
And sometimes C.K.
would let out expletives that would waft into our room, and you could see the red on Carl Landon's neck starting just above his very white starch collar and going up to his silver hair.
I remember one time asking Carl, what was the secret of good officiating?
He said, call them fast and walk away tough.
That's right.
That's really good advice.
Did he have any guidelines, any rules?
You were mentioning the neatness and tidiness.
Were there any other...

Oh, as physical education majors, when we did our student teaching, we had to wear white pants, contradiction in terms, but kind of like white khakis, the canvas type pants, and the white t-shirt with physical education emblazoned across the chest.
And you wore that every day for your practice teaching, and it better be clean and pressed.
You did the end of your undergraduate degree here, and then your Ph.D. My master's here.
Your master's, okay.
Then your Ph.D. at North Texas.
At North Texas.
So you came as intramural director.
Correct.
Describe intramural, or intramural program at that time.
It was a large program for a school this size.
There were 55 units on campus.
mostly in the military.
In most cases, we had 110 teams because the freshmen competed separately from the sophomores and above.
And with the Corps, there was not any doubt if a team would be fielded in every sport because there would be.
One of the real strengths, I think, of the program at that time was they depended on student managers.
And there were a fairly large number of sophomore managers.
Rather, acceptance dropped to the junior managers.
And then you usually had about four to six senior managers.
And they really ran the program.
Were they, in effect, the coaches?
They were the officials.
They were the ones who took all the equipment out to the field.
They did almost all of it.
The sophomores got a maroon sweater with the intramural seal on it.
The juniors got a white one.
And the seniors got a watch.
I calculated the time.
For the seniors, they got about a nickel an hour for what they did.
And one of the things I thought was really interesting was that there were more engineering students who served as intramural managers than any other college.
And here is one of the most demanding time requirements and in the core, and yet they became the leaders in intramurals.
How many sports?
Probably about 32 different sports.
Yeah.
What were the, by today's standards, what were some of the perhaps unusual?
Horseshoes.
That was the most unusual, I think.
Everyone ran cross-country, which I thought was really demanding because most of them had not trained very far, very long for it, and they'd go out and almost all of them finished.
And that was before running was as much of a craze as it is today.
Were there, by today's standards, some omissions?
Was soccer included?
We did not have soccer.
But volleyball, it was a really comprehensive program.
Badminton, swimming, diving.
Art Adamson would go over and really, in essence, run the swimming and diving.
He, too, ran a tight ship.
And those contests occurred normally where?
on what we now call the Duncan Drill Field, on occasion on the main drill field, but we didn't have access to that very often.
But we had different areas around the campus.
Some of them I shuttered in and shuttered out.
On the softball fields, they had concrete bases and never wore out.
And no one ever stole one down there.
But thought of all the dangers that could have been associated with those.
The tennis courts were over not very far from the Grove.
We used the Grove for some of the events.
DeWare was where Intramurals was located when I came back.
So it was a program I think anyone would ever be very proud of.
Mr. Penberthy was the founder of the entrepreneurial program.
And then Spike White and then Bonnie Welch.
And that's a pretty elite group of people.
You say he founded it, was it during the 30s, 20s?
I think the 20s.
I think about 27, if I remember correctly.
And Mr. Penberthy was still around.
Describe him.
Oh, Mr. Penberthy was a wonderful, wonderful person.
One of his great attributes was remembering everyone's name.
And even when he went back into physical education, after he'd been one of the upper level administrators, he came back and volleyball was a sport that he really took over.
And volleyball had just gotten a lot of recognition by television of the Olympics.
And Mr. Penberthy was nearing the end of his professional career, but he learned a great deal about volleyball.
Went out to watch a good volleyball team play, and came back and taught good volleyball in the physical education program at A&M.
At that time, almost everyone was in the Corps, and everyone wore a white t-shirt, maroon shorts, and Mr. Penberthy had
about 48 students in class.
By the third class, we were keeping every student's name.
When you see all 18-year-old males with the military haircut and white t-shirts and running short, there's not a lot to distinguish those people from each other.
Alright, so you do intramurals for how long?
Until 63, a relatively short period of time.
And then?
Then I went to education in psychology.
And at that time, it was a combined department.
And I taught psychology and educational psychology.
In a short period of time, I became the director of the freshman courses, which were courses that had been taught in the basic division, study skills, job orientation, and some things like that.
And who was the head of the education?
Paul Eastman, the scrum head.
Paul Henseling was a former school superintendent.
Again, I'd say that he was one of them.
He represented the profession very well.
He thought education was a tremendously important area of the university and represented it well.
And education is one of those disciplines that I think is always suspect in the school, such as A&M.
One of the things that I learned while I was here was that even when A&M was very small, it was the number two
University in producing male teachers in the state of Texas, which I think very few people ever recognized.
But with the vocational agriculture and vocational education and health and physical education in particular, the Aggie produced a lot of high school teachers.
Now the department was the Department on?
Education and Psychology.
And it remained a department only until
I think it was 1973.
You can probably help me on that.
That's right.
Somewhere in there.
And the department was housed where?
In the academic building.
Fourth floor of the academic building.
And the department during those years was about how many and number of faculty?
I just have to make a guess.
probably 20.

And then when they divided the department, education and psychology, and then they divided the college, just prior to that, they'd separate the College of Business Administration out of the College of Liberal Arts.
And then for a short period of time,
Dean Hubert served as dean of liberal arts and the head of education and psychology.
And I think you've heard this story.
I still think it's a good story.
I was the associate dean.
And one day, I was in Dean Hubert's office in the academic building.
And he was determined that he would do no business for education and psychology in the dean's office on the first floor of that building and no
liberal arts business in the department's office in the fourth floor.
But one day I was in his office and we were visiting and he was shuffling through papers around the desk.
And I saw him get something to Frank W.R. Hubert, dean of the College of Liberal Arts from Frank W.R. Hubert, interim head of education and psychology.
And he wrote very large letters, denied.
and said, Chuck, those damn department heads will ask for anything.
And I thought that was, I thought that was Franky.
As department head, he felt obliged to ask for it.
And as dean, he determined that it wasn't wanted.
So, as you joined the faculty, the teaching faculty, non-compulsory core, co-education,
racial integration, all of those changes are getting started right about then.
How did that affect education?
It affected it in a lot of ways.
And incidentally, one of the things that I have believed for a long while, when they talk about integration in Indiana, they're talking about women.
I honestly cannot remember any difficulty in accepting blacks.
but there was a great deal of emotion in accepting women.
All right.
Now, on that topic, share any that you can recall.
Well, one of the things that, again, one of the things that I enjoyed, in physical education, they were talking about how are we going to accommodate these women.

And so they were trying to make decisions about locker rooms and where there would be modifications and how would we do all this and how would we do all that and what activities would be available for women.
and the hiring of women faculty members and all those things.
And so someone asked Art Adamson, how are you going to take care of them?
And Art's response was, hell, that ain't no problem.
I'll give them a cap, a strap, and two band-aids.
Did the enrollment numbers change?
Didn't change dramatically at first because, as I'm sure you know, the first change was the change in the name and the change in women's being eligible to come to A&M.
was for faculty family, student wives, and women seeking an advanced degree and not readily available at other Texas institutions, which meant the vet school.
There were no real changes in the facilities at that time, that I remember.
And then I think three years later, they opened it up to all women.
And the real change was when they built
Kruger-Dunn-Bosier-Aston complex, and we started officially housing them on campus.
And that made a world of difference.
Did that make a difference in the education world?
Oh, dramatically.
Dramatically.
It wasn't very long until there were more female majors than there were male majors.
Let's go back to education and so forth.
Frank Hubert was Dean of Arts and Sciences.
That's correct.
Describe your view of him when you were a junior faculty member.
Frank Hubert
I didn't have a lot of association with him as a junior faculty member.
I really got to know Frankie well.
I'm going to go back and forth.
But when I first met him, when I was applying for a job, he was very business-like.
There was not a great deal of warmth in our meeting.
So he was involved in the interview process?
Yes.
I came across, like I said, very, very serious, very matter of fact, very direct.
Then I got to know them a little better and in the summers I taught at the adjunct in Junction.
In 61 until 63, I think.
The last year I was the director of the adjunct.
But that summer,
I got a phone call.
I had, I had just been offered to become Department Head of Educational Psychology, and that was something I thought I might want to do.
Now this is about when?
About 16, 16, find out.
I can, I can find out.
Sure, no, that's all right.
But anyway, Frank Hubert called me from the
when I was at the adjunct and told me that he'd like for me to be the assistant dean of liberal arts.
And so I came back and I visited with him and he was telling me about it and I told him that I had just been offered the job in the department head of ed science which was a brand new department.
And he offered the job to me again and I was
to commit, and the third time I realized he really wasn't asking.
He was telling me that he would like me to be the assistant dean.
And then something I thought was really strange was after I'd agreed, he said, now, Chuck, I want you to understand that there's no commitment that's going to continue.
He said, we're going to have a national search.
And I thought, whoa.
What is this?
But anyway.
I did accept the job and very shortly thereafter I was made the associate dean.
And then when they divided liberal arts and education, I was given the choice of going to education or staying with liberal arts and for one year I served the associate dean of both colleges.
And then opted to stay with liberal arts.
So it was an interesting transition.
And as you asked earlier, the nature of the college was just changing very, very rapidly.
The offices that were located then were liberal arts.
First floor of the academic building.
Academic building.
Share some more Hubert anecdotes that demonstrate his operational style.

OK. One of the things that I thought was meaningful that I'm not sure he thought much about, but when he was designing the offices for the dean of arts and sciences, he planned the dean's office on the fifth floor of the biology building.
And when they separated science out, then he stayed with liberal arts.
But I'm not sure he ever thought about that the fifth floor of the biology building is certainly not on the path to any different.
You have to make a special trip to go there.
The location of the dean's office for liberal arts, which I'm not sure how that was chosen,
that was on the first floor of the academic building, which was on the road to everywhere.
And so I really thought that was the ideal place for a dean's office because it was so easy for the students to have access to, and the faculty.
But that was not where the dean of science office was and is.
What about his temperament?
humor, anger, patience.
All those.
He had all those.
He was one of the most astute political readers I've ever known.
He read things very well.
And I think his basic nature is reserved, restrained,
introvert, but I've never seen anyone who could be more effective in smoothing people.
He could move among groups and know exactly what to say, say it extremely well, and then move to the next group and make everyone feel that they'd had his undivided attention for that period of time.
It's a skill that I wish that I had someone who could even approach, but
But that was a real strength.
He had some health problems, and I think there were times that his health problems created a situation where he did not come across his back in particular.
I'll rely on your judgment on this, but one of the things that I remember
when someone was retiring who had worked in his office.
And he'd had a little more to drink than he probably should have before he responded.
But he started out by saying, you know, when I first went to work for Frank Hubert, I thought of him like he lived as a cold fish.
And I looked at Dean Hubert, and it looked as though someone had hit him with a wet towel.
He just could not imagine that that's how anyone would see him.

But the man went on quickly, seemingly quickly, to say that after he got to work with Frank Hubert and realized what a warm human being he really is, and that was his message, not the first part, but I'm not sure that Dean Hubert ever heard the last part of that.
He was...
He was a very decisive person.
He had strong opinions, made judgments quickly about people, some of which I thought were very astute and some of which I thought were considerably off-mark.
I thought the same about my judgment.
But were there some key decisions about
liberal arts and or education, which you now look back and see those were important decisions, plus or minus.
Well, I think that the division of arts and sciences, again, is a major factor.
If you think about A&M today, and you think about geology, and you think about chemistry, physics, all those that are in there, business administration,
was under liberal arts at that point.
There were really a lot of very major transitions that from my point of view occurred very smoothly.
I didn't feel any great bumps in the road as we went along, and I think Frank Hubert deserves a lot of credit for not being threatened by that, but believing that that was the essential
in the evolution of a real university.
Q Do you have any idea how much role he played in deciding that those divisions would come about?
A I can't imagine that he didn't have a major role.
Frank Huber, as I said, was a very effective administrator.
While he was in the dean's office and all that,
I thought he was as effective as any administrator that I had known, and I gave him the political ability to evaluate a situation that I thought was absolutely essential.
I don't think that most of those things would have happened smoothly, if at all, had he really resisted them.
I think he was instrumental.
What was his relationship with
Vice President Call and President Rudd?
It seemed to me that he had a very close relationship with them.

I didn't see him with Wayne Hall very often, but I would have liked to have been there and just watched the glib pattern that went back and forth between the two, because they were both very serious people.
one of the stories which I will share that I enjoyed.
